Business Understanding 1 ¶

Describe the purpose of the data set you selected (i.e., why was this data collected in the first place?)¶

This dataset was collected to model and predict prices for used cars and trucks listed for sale on Craigslist U.S. regional sites. For this project, classification and clustering techniques are used to predict the price range of a car. We are using 'Craigslist cars and trucks data' from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/austinreese/craigslist-carstrucks-data. The author of this dataset used web scraping algorithms to gather information for used vehicles from all regional Craigslist sites in the U.S that were posted between 10/28/2020 and 12/3/2020. The original dataset contained 458,213 rows with 26 fields. After cleaning the data in Lab 1, the final dataset has 137,526 rows and 16 columns.

How will you measure the effectiveness of a good algorithm?¶

We will be using clustering techniques in this project with the goal of adding the cluster outputs to a Random Forest classification model to see if the clusters add any value to the selected classification model. Random Forest was chosen because it produced the best model with this dataset in Lab 2.

Evaluating Clusters:

  • Silhouette Score: The Silhouette score will be used to assess the effectiveness of a clustering technique. The Silhouette coefficient is used to compute the density of clusters by the model when the ground truth about the dataset is unknown. The score is computed by averaging the Silhouette coefficient for each sample, computed as the difference between the average intra-cluster distance and the mean nearest-cluster distance for each sample, normalized by the maximum value. This produces a score between -1 and 1, where 1 is highly dense clusters and -1 is completely incorrect clustering.
    Reference: https://www.scikit-yb.org/en/latest/api/cluster/silhouette.html
  • Gini Index: Gini Index, also known as Gini impurity, calculates the amount of probability of a specific feature that is classified incorrectly when selected randomly. If all the elements are linked with a single class then it is considered pure. Gini index values vary between values 0 and 1, where 0 expresses the purity of classification, i.e. all the elements belong to a specified class or only one class exists there. And 1 indicates the random distribution of elements across various classes. The value of 0.5 of the Gini Index shows an equal distribution of elements over some classes.
    Reference: https://medium.com/analytics-steps/understanding-the-gini-index-and-information-gain-in-decision-trees-ab4720518ba8

Evaluating Classification Models: For each clustering technique, we will add the cluster output as a feature to the dataset, we will then create classification models to evaluate if the corrsponding clusters help improve model performance. We will perform 10-fold cross validation and the following validation metrics will be used to assess the performance of the classification models:

  • Accuracy: Accuracy measures the number of correct predictions by dividing the correct predictions by total predictions. The overall accuracy of each model will be measured.
  • Precision: Precision is how accurate a model is when a positive prediction is made. It is a measurement of True Positive predictions divided by Total Positive predictions. Because this is a five-class problem, Precision will be evaluated for each class and averaged over all the classes to get a Precision value for each model.
  • Recall: Recall is how accurate a model is at identifying True Positives. It is measured by dividing True Positive predictions by Actual Positive values. This will also be measured by class and averaged.
  • F1: The F1 score attempts to balance Precision and Recall metrics. Because this analysis does not the require preference of one over the other, this score will be evaluated as well. These metrics are measured as a pecentage between 0 - 100 with higher scores indicating a better predictive model. As the response variable in this dataset is balanced, Accuracy is a good indicator of the overall model performance. In predicting the price_range of a car, we are not biased towards false positives or false negatives. Thus, we will be paying more attention to the overall F1 score of the models.

Why does your chosen validation method make sense for this specific dataset and the stakeholders needs?¶

The reason for the collection of this data was to predict the price/price-range of a car listed on Craigslist. We have built Classification models for this purpose and have also implemented clustering techniques. Stakeholders would be interested in how accurate the classification model is. Therefore, the above mentioned metrics of assessing classification models are appropriate. As we are adding clusters to this dataset, it is important to see how much information gain can be achieved with the clusters. Thus, the silhouette score and gini index play an important role in assessing the clusters.

Describe the meaning and type of data (scale, values, etc.) for each attribute in the data file.¶

The original dataset contained 458,213 rows with 26 fields. We cleaned the dataset as part of Lab 1 and our final dataset has 137,526 rows and 16 columns. Verify data quality: Are there missing values? Duplicate data? Outliers? Are those mistakes? How do you deal with these problems?¶

As part of Lab 1, we performed EDA on the original dataset (458,213 rows and 26 fields) and found a lot of missing values, duplicate data, and outliers. Some of the these seemed to be mistakes as well. The following was done to handle each of these scenarios:

Missing Values¶

Several attributes had missing values in the original dataset. We retrieved missing values from the U.S. Department of Transportation VIN API: https://vpic.nhtsa.dot.gov/api/. A scraper was built to call a ReST endpoint and write the details to a file, which was later joined to the original dataset. After retrieving all available missing data, there were still rows with missing values for important attributes. These rows were dropped from the dataset.
Further details on how missing values were handled can be found in the Lab 1 -> Data Quality-> Missing Values section.

Duplicate Data¶

There were duplicate records in the dataset because the same car could be listed in multiple regions. We identified duplicate records by checking whether a vehicle instance was unique across all columns in the dataset. If there were multiple records with identical values, then the duplicate records were removed.
We also created new features to handle some of the inconsistent values that had the same meaning, e.g., in the 'Drive' column, there were values of '4wd' and 'Four wd.' These values were recategorized into a new column (see 'New features' section below).

Outliers¶

The price, year, and odometer columns had some major outliers. A lot of the extreme outliers seemed to be mistakes (e.g., USD 3.5 billion for price, 1900 for year). We implemented a quantile method to screen out the outliers. We set the upper limit for the quantile to be 0.99 and lower limit to be 0.01.

Price, Year and Odometer box plots before removing outliers: From the plot below, the original dataset had extreme values between USD 2.5M and 3.5B. These were removed from the dataset. Reference: Lab 1 Jupyter notebook. Please see Lab 1 'Outlier's section for code details.

We had a few outliers for Year (year built) between 1900 - 1910. These were removed from the dataset.

Similarly, we had outliers for 'Odometer' with a few cars having extremly high odometer readings of 3 million miles. This must be a mistake, but because there is no way to get the correct odometer reading for these rows, we handled them as outliers and removed them from the dataset.

Mistakes¶

As stated in the outliers section above, a lot of extreme outliers in the price, year and odometer columns seemed to be mistakes. We did not correct any of these, but instead removed them from the dataset using a quantile method to screen out the outliers.

New features created in Lab 1¶

As part of Lab 1, the following features were created:

  1. price_range: The price column was split into multiple price ranges and a categorical column was created. We regrouped these values for project 2 into more balanced classes. Price_range is grouped into the following values: 'Less than 5K','5K-9K','9K-15K','15K-24K','>24K'. These values are then coded into a corresponding integer value of 0 through 4.

  2. car_Age_in_yrs: A new field for age of the car was derived by subtracting the year of the car from the posting date.

  3. The following columns were recategorized by grouping similar values:

    ii) condition_new from condition

Most Important Attributes
The most important attributes in the dataset are odometer, car_Age_in_yrs, and cylinders based on the impurity score from a Random Forest classification model as shown in the Random Forest feature importance plot above. Even though cylinders is the 3rd most important attribute, we can see from the bar plot that the importance of the feature is much lower than odometer and car_Age_in_years. The weight of importance for odometer and car_Age_in_yrs is over 0.2, while the weight for cylinders is only 0.05

We can see that the odometer has the most importance in determining the price range classification of a car. This observation makes sense as we know that the value of a car depreciates with increasing mileage. It is a common indicator of wear and tear on a car and cars that are new with fewer miles can typically command higher prices in the used car market. The next most importance feature is the car_Age_in_yrs. Again, common knowledge tells us that the value of a car depreciates with increased age. We can also say that there is correlation between age of cars and odometer as cars with a higher age tend to have higher odometer readings. The third most important feature is cylinders. Typically, a higher number of cylinders is associated with premium / sports cars, which are usually not sold at lower values in the used car markets. Normally trucks have six or more cylinders and therefore it makes sense to see that trucks are also negatively correlated with the price segment.

Modeling and Evaluation 1 ¶

**Train and adjust parameters**

The following clustering models will be trained and tuned: KMeans, DBSCAN, Spectral, and Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering (HAC).

KMeans¶

KMeans is a clustering algorithm that groups similiar data together in order to discover similiarities. The parameters tuned are:

  • n_clusters: The number of clusters and number of centroids to generate. The default is 8. A range of values between 1 and 10 will be tested. The elbow method will be used to determine the optimal number.

For the other parameters, the default values are used. K-means++ is the default value for the 'init' parameter and we chose to use this to help speed up the convergence.

Reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.cluster.KMeans.html

The elbow method is used to find the optimal number of clusters (n_clusters)¶

In [33]:
#find optimal n_clusters via the elbow method

for i in range(1, 11):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', n_init=10, max_iter=300, random_state=42)

DBSCAN¶

DBSCAN is a density based clustering algorithm. The parameters tuned here are:

  • eps: The maximum distance between two samples for one to be considered in the neighborhood of the other. The default is 0.5. A range of values between 0.5 and 5.0 will be tested.
  • min_samples: The number of samples in a neighborhood for a point to be considered a core point. The default is 5. A range of values between 3 to 5 will be tested.

Reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.cluster.DBSCAN.html

Spectral Clustering¶

Spectral Clustering is a clustering algorithm that uses eigenvalues of matrices built from the dataset to determine the best clustering. PCA will be used to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset and the parameters tuned here are:

  • n_clusters: The dimension of the projection subspace. The default is 8. A range of clusters will be tested.
  • affinity: This sets how to construct the affinity matrix. The default is 'rbf.' 'rbf', 'nearest_neighbors', and 'precomputed' will be tested.

Reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.cluster.SpectralClustering.html

When Spectral Clustering was run on the full dataset and subsets of 30,000 or 20,000 instances, there was a memory error: "MemoryError: Unable to allocate 141. GiB for an array with shape (137526, 137526) and data type float64". 10,000 instances had no issues with memory errors so that is used below.

The elbow curve is used to find the optimum number of clusters (n_clusters)¶

In [43]:
# references: http://github.com/ciortanmadalina/high_noise_clustering/blob/master/spectral_clustering.ipynb

import scipy
from scipy.sparse import csgraph
# from scipy.sparse.linalg import eigsh
from numpy import linalg as LA
def eigenDecomposition(A, plot = True, topK = 5):
    """
    :param A: Affinity matrix
    :param plot: plots the sorted eigen values for visual inspection
    :return A tuple containing:
    - the optimal number of clusters by eigengap heuristic
    - all eigen values
    - all eigen vectors
    
    This method performs the eigen decomposition on a given affinity matrix,
    following the steps recommended in the paper:
    1. Construct the normalized affinity matrix: L = D1/2AD 1/2.
    2. Find the eigenvalues and their associated eigen vectors
    3. Identify the maximum gap which corresponds to the number of clusters
    by eigengap heuristic
    
    References:
    https://papers.nips.cc/paper/2619-self-tuning-spectral-clustering.pdf
    http://www.kyb.mpg.de/fileadmin/user_upload/files/publications/attachments/Luxburg07_tutorial_4488%5b0%5d.pdf
    """
    L = csgraph.laplacian(A, normed=True)
    n_components = A.shape[0]
    
    # LM parameter : Eigenvalues with largest magnitude (eigs, eigsh), that is, largest eigenvalues in 
    # the euclidean norm of complex numbers.
#     eigenvalues, eigenvectors = eigsh(L, k=n_components, which="LM", sigma=1.0, maxiter=5000)
    eigenvalues, eigenvectors = LA.eig(L)
    
    if plot:
        plt.title('Largest eigen values of input matrix')
        plt.scatter(np.arange(len(eigenvalues)), eigenvalues)
        plt.grid()
        
    # Identify the optimal number of clusters as the index corresponding
    # to the larger gap between eigen values
    index_largest_gap = np.argsort(np.diff(eigenvalues))[::-1][:topK]
    nb_clusters = index_largest_gap + 1
        
    return nb_clusters, eigenvalues, eigenvectors
In [44]:
# references: http://github.com/ciortanmadalina/high_noise_clustering/blob/master/spectral_clustering.ipynb

from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist, squareform
def getAffinityMatrix(coordinates, k = 7):
    """
    Calculate affinity matrix based on input coordinates matrix and the number
    of nearest neighbours.
    
    Apply local scaling based on the k nearest neighbour
        References:
    https://papers.nips.cc/paper/2619-self-tuning-spectral-clustering.pdf
    """
    # calculate euclidian distance matrix
    dists = squareform(pdist(coordinates)) 
    
    # for each row, sort the distances ascendingly and take the index of the 
    #k-th position (nearest neighbour)
    knn_distances = np.sort(dists, axis=0)[k]
    knn_distances = knn_distances[np.newaxis].T
    
    # calculate sigma_i * sigma_j
    local_scale = knn_distances.dot(knn_distances.T)

    affinity_matrix = dists * dists
    affinity_matrix = -affinity_matrix / local_scale
    # divide square distance matrix by local scale
    affinity_matrix[np.where(np.isnan(affinity_matrix))] = 0.0
    # apply exponential
    affinity_matrix = np.exp(affinity_matrix)
    np.fill_diagonal(affinity_matrix, 0)
    return affinity_matrix

Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering (HAC)¶

Agglomerative Clustering is a clustering algorithm that builds a hierarchy of clusters. The parameters tuned below are:

  • n_clusters: The number of clusters. The default is 2. A range of values between 1 and 10 will be tested.
  • linkage: This determines which distance to use between sets of observations. The default is 'ward.' 'ward', 'average', and 'complete' will be tested.

Reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.cluster.AgglomerativeClustering.html

In [53]:

Conclusion: Evaluate and Compare¶

Below are is a summary of results for each clustering method.

In [89]:
results_df
Out[89]:
model n_clusters silhouette acc (baseline) acc (with clusters) precision recall f1
0 KMeans 3 0.5698 82.24 82.12 82.14 82.12 82.13
1 DBSCAN 19984 0.2205 82.24 82.06 82.09 82.06 82.07
2 Spectral* 260 0.2937 71.16 71.04 71.12 71.04 71.06
3 HAC* 2 0.5833 67.46 67.68 67.67 67.68 67.67

*The Spectral model was run on 10K samples because of memory constraints using the full dataset. The HAC model was run on 5K samples for the same reason.

To evaluate and compare clustering techniques, we generated a new cluster feature based on the best parameters from training/adjusting the cluster models. The new feature was then added to the dataset before running the Random Forest Classification model again. The results were compared to a baseline Random Forest classification model without the cluster feature.

After adding each cluster feature to Random Forest Classification model, the KMeans clusters produced the highest metrics with an accuracy of 82.12, precision of 82.14, recall of 82.12, and f1 score of 82.13. However, only the HAC model improved with the cluster features and the improvement was very minor from 67.46% to 67.68% accuracy.

The number of clusters for KMeans, Spectral, and HAC was selected based on the highest silhouette score in Modeling in Evaluation 2 when training and adjusting parameters. DBSCAN is a density based algorithm that chooses the ideal number of clusters. The number chosen was almost 20,000. The silhouette score is only 0.22 which indicates that this is not a good clustering algorithm.

HAC model produced the highest silhouette score of 0.5833. This was the only model that showed a minor improvement on the baseline model.

from matplotlib import cm

km = KMeans(n_clusters=3, init='k-means++', n_init=10, max_iter=300, tol=1e-04, random_state=42)
y_km = km.fit_predict(X)

cluster_labels = np.unique(y_km)
n_clusters = cluster_labels.shape[0]
silhouette_vals = silhouette_samples(X, y_km, metric='euclidean')
y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper = 0, 0
yticks = []
for i, c in enumerate(cluster_labels):
    c_silhouette_vals = silhouette_vals[y_km == c]
    c_silhouette_vals.sort()
    y_ax_upper += len(c_silhouette_vals)
    color = cm.jet(float(i) / n_clusters)
    plt.barh(range(y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper), c_silhouette_vals, height=1.0, 
             edgecolor='none', color=color)

    yticks.append((y_ax_lower + y_ax_upper) / 2.)
    y_ax_lower += len(c_silhouette_vals)
    
silhouette_avg_km = np.mean(silhouette_vals)
print(silhouette_avg_km)

Modeling and Evaluation 4 ¶

Summarize the Ramifications

Building clusters¶

In this project, we built clusters using the following clustering techniques: KMeans, DBSCAN, Spectral and Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering.
To build the most efficient clusters on this dataset, we trained and adjusted the hyperparameters below for each clustering algorithm. The set of parameters that provided the best (highest) silhouette score was then picked and the final clustering algorithms were implemented:

  • Kmeans: n_clusters = 3
  • DBScan: eps = 3.0 and min_samples = 3
  • Spectral Clustering: n_clusters = 260 and affinity = 'nearest neighbors'
  • HAC: n_clusters = 2 and linkage = 'average'

Visualizing clusters¶

To gain insights on the clusters, we created the following visualizations:

  • KMeans: The Silhouette Visualizer displays the silhouette coefficient for each sample on a per-cluster basis, visualizing which clusters are dense and which are not. This is particularly useful for determining cluster imbalance, or for selecting a value for K by comparing multiple visualizers. We used this plot to visualize cluster imbalance. As this visualization only works for centroidal clustering algorithms, we created it for KMeans only.
  • DBSCAN and Spectral: Scatter plots were created using Principal Components. With 121 features in the dataset, to visualize the various clusters efficiently, we created PC1 and PC2 and embedded clusters on top of them. As both of these algorithms created high number of clusters (260 for DBScan and ~19K for Spectral), the visualizations could not show a clear distinction on all the clusters but it was very clear for a few of them.
  • Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering: The Dendrogram plot provided a clear picture of the 2 clusters that the Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering algorithm created. It also provided diagrammatic representation of the hierarchical relationship between the dat-points.
  • Feature Importance Bar Plots: After running the Random Forest Classifier with a new 'cluster' feature, we selected the top 10 features from Feature Importance to plot the feature weights. KMeans, DBSCAN, and HAC showed that the 'cluster' feature was the 4th most important feature. Spectral Clustering resulted in the 'cluster' feature as the 3rd most important feature.

These visualizations can be seen in the section 'Modeling and Evaluation 3'.

Passing the cluster output to the Random Forest Classifier¶

After finding the optimal hyperparameters for each clustering algorithm, we added the cluster output as a new feature to the dataset, this new feature was then used to build a classification model. As part of Lab 2, the Random Forest Classification model produced the best performance metrics on this dataset. We picked this model and used it as a baseline to compare to the new model with the cluster output added as a new feature. To get the accuracy, precision, recall, and f1 score, 10-fold cross validation was run on each Random Forest Classifier model.

The following table summarizes the results for the Random Forest Classfication model with the new feature for each clustering technique:

Number of Clusters
The number of clusters for these models ranges from 2 to 19,984. For KMeans and HAC, the values for this parameter were selected based on hypertuning results - the value that produced the best silhouette scores for the parameters tested made it into the final model. The number of clusters for DBSCAN is determined by the model directly, rather than choosing the value to pass to the model. For DBSCAN, after tuning the eps and min_samples to get the highest silhouette score, the model determined that 19,984 was the optimal number of clusters. DBSCAN and Spectral have a much higher number of clusters and the silhouette scores are the lowest for these models.

Silhouette Scores
HAC and KMeans have the highest silhouette scores, but this does not translate to better metrics for the model. The highest silhouette score was 0.5833 for the HAC model and it was the only model that showed a minor improvement in accuracy by about 0.22%.

Performance Metrics
The clustering feature for HAC slightly improved the classification model metrics. The other three show a minor decrease between 0.12% to 0.53% after the clusters were added. This was surprising as we expected there to be some improvement. We thought the Spectral clusters might improve the model because of the nice separation of clusters in the visualization. However, this model had a low silhouette score which might be the reason that it did not improve the accuracy of the model. HAC had the highest silhouette score and it was the only model that showed an improved accuracy, but it was a very small improvement.

# feature ranking thru gini index definition
#Code provided by Dr. Drew
def gini_index(y):
    probs=pd.value_counts(y, normalize=True)
    return 1-np.sum(np.square(probs))

While a lot of these values are low, indicating purity of the corresponding clusters but majority (indicated by mean) are on the higher side, indicating high impurity. A consistent low gini index for the clusters might have contributed towards the improved accuracy of the Random Forest model, but in our case, because a lot of high values of gini index, we did not see any improvement in the accuracy of the Random Forest Classification model with this adding new feature.

HAC Gini Index Plot
The bar plot above shows the Gini Index for the 2 clusters that were created using the Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering technique. The Gini index was calculated by assessing the number of different classes in each cluster. We see that both these clusters had approximately the same value of Gini Index which is around 0.67, looking closely cluster number 0 has a gini index of 0.67 and cluster number 1 has 0.675. These values for Gini index look to be on a higher side. And also, because we have 5 classes but only 2 clusters were created for this clustering technique, a higher impurity was expected. We believe, this might be the reason why the output of this clustering technique very minimally helped the accuracy of the Random Forest Classifier Model.

Deployment ¶

Be critical of your performance and tell the reader how your current model might be usable by other parties. Did you achieve your goals? If not, can you reign in the utility of your modeling? How useful is your model for interested parties (i.e., the companies or organizations that might want to use it)? How would your deploy your model for interested parties? What other data should be collected? How often would the model need to be updated, etc.?.

Be critical of your performance and tell the reader how your current model might be usable by other parties?
The goal of this project was to predict the price range of a car based on the available Craig's list attributes such as Model, manufacturer, condition, odometer reading, year built etc. We got up to 82% accuracy using Random Forest classification. We believe this is pretty good and that this model could be a useful research tool for individuals buying or selling a vehicle on Craig's list. We built clustering features based on various algorithms, but only Spectral Clustering had a minor improvement to the accuracy of the Random Forest model.

Did you achieve your goals?
Yes, we believe we achieved the goal of this project of predicting the price range of Craig's list used cars. The best model had an accuracy of 82% which we feel is pretty good. Adding clusters to the model did not improve the model. Clustering can be used in EDA, but building the Random Forest classifier on the dataset (without cluster features) should be sufficient.

If not, can you reign in the utility of your modeling?
We could do better by overcoming the following challenges:

  1. Missing values: Our initial dataset had 458,213 rows but a lot of the data was missing. We did bring few attributes from the US Dept. of Transporation, but still there were attributes that had missing information. We had to drop all those rows.
  2. Outliers: We had various outliers, could have been mistakes but the extreme ones were handled as outliers and were removed from the dataset.

    3. The above two reasons contributed to us dropping more than half of our dataset. We could probably improve the performance of our model if we could find a way to impute most of these variables (for ex: clustering could be use to impute categorical variables).

  3. Computing power: Our final dataset had 121 features and 137,526 instances. There were several models where our computers could not handle this size of the dataset and would get memory errors, thus for those models, we had to limit our dataset to 10K or 5K random samples. We believe we could have done better if we had more computing power or knew ways to handle the dataset of this size using our current available computing power.
  4. More models to explore?: We tried all the models and methods that we learned in this class, it will be interesting to see what we learn in the next classes and see if those help us further improve the performance of our model.

How useful is your model for interested parties (i.e., the companies or organizations that might want to use it)?
This model could be a useful research tool for individuals buying or selling a vehicle on Craig's list. In general, we believe this tool will add a lot of value to any company that sells used cars (training data and deployment methods might vary by company), it will help save time for both the sellers and buyers by suggesting sellers the appropriate selling price and buyers the appropriate market price.

  • Sellers: This tool will help set competitive pricing for the car that the seller is about to list or has already listed. Or if a seller is having trouble getting responses to a listing, this tool could help with price correction.
  • Buyers: A buyer who is interested in a particular car may want to find out if the asking price is fair compared to the other listings. This could save a buyer time by avoiding clicking through many car listings to manually compare car features and prices and would make decision making quicker.

How would you deploy your model for interested parties?

Sellers: The relevant features of the car would be gathered from a web form and passed to a trained model. The model would make a prediction and return it to the seller. The seller could choose to use the prediction or set a different price.

Buyers: The application would gather the car's features, pass them to the model, and return an estimated price or price range for the car. Craig's list could also display an icon or symbol indicating whether a car is a good price, similar to the "Good Deal" tag on cars.com where a vehicle's price and features are compared to similiar cars (see example below). The "Good Deal" tag would require an additional calculation to compare the prediction to an actual listing price.

To take it one step further, it would be useful to present information to the buyer about which features are driving the cost of a car to be higher or lower than other similiar cars. For example, a car without a title might explain why its price is lower than other cars with similiar features. Because the data used to train the model is from Craig's list, the model only makes sense for that site in its current form, but it could be re-trained and deployed to other used car sites with the appropriate data.

What other data should be collected?
We believe the current attributes collected captured all the details of the used cars but the following suggestions could add quality to this dataset and might help build better models:

  1. Adding Mandatory fields on the web form: We saw missing values in a lot of fields, we believe few fields such as Model, State, manufacturer, odometer reading, Year built, cylinders etc. would always be known to a seller and could be made mandatory.
  2. Data validation on the web form to avoid extreme outliers.
  3. We could also have additional sources like Kelly Blue Book data presented along with these predictions as another point of comparison when buyers or sellers are trying to gain insights into used car prices.

How often would the model need to be updated, etc.?.
Ideally, this model would be re-trained with new listings once per week and would include the most recent four weeks of data in order to stay relevant with current market conditions. Only inactive or retired listings would be used to train the model. This may require using data a month or two in the past.

For any of these tools, there should be a disclaimer that the predicted prices are based on past Craig's list vehicle listings in the set date range and may not reflect the quality or the true value of the car.

KMeans Intercluster Distance Map
The above intercluster distance plot is showing an embedding of cluster centers in 2 dimensional space with the distance to the other centers preserved using the KMeans clustering algorithm. The number of clusters is 3 with the default embedding value of multidimensional scaling (MDS). Clusters closer to the center of the plot indicate that the clusters are closer to the original feature space. Cluster 0 and 2 look closer to the center compared to Cluster 1. Cluster 1 seems to be the farthest away from the center, which indicates a sparse cluster. The smaller the cluster is on the plot, the smaller the number of points. Cluster 1 has the smallest cluster drawn which means it has the smallest number of points for that cluster whereas cluster 2 is the biggest cluster indicating that it has the largest number of points.
